## Why Performance Matters

Application performance directly impacts user retention, conversion rates, and accessibility. A 100ms delay in response time can reduce conversion rates by 7%. Slow React apps frustrate users, hurt SEO rankings, and drain battery life on mobile devices.

## Measuring Before Optimizing

Never optimize blindly. Establish baselines using:

- **React DevTools Profiler**: Visualize component re-renders and identify expensive renders
- **Lighthouse**: Score performance, accessibility, and best practices
- **Web Vitals** (LCP, FID, CLS): Core user-centric metrics tracked by Google

```jsx
import { Profiler } from "react";

function onRender(id, phase, actualDuration) {
  console.log(`${id} (${phase}): ${actualDuration}ms`);
}

<Profiler id="Dashboard" onRender={onRender}>
  <Dashboard />
</Profiler>
```

Profile in production-like conditions. Development mode is significantly slower than production builds.

## Memoization Strategies

### React.memo

Wrap components that receive the same props to skip unnecessary re-renders:

```jsx
const ExpenseRow = React.memo(function ExpenseRow({ item }) {
  return <tr><td>{item.name}</td><td>{item.amount}</td></tr>;
});
```

### useMemo and useCallback

Use `useMemo` to cache expensive computations and `useCallback` to stabilize callback references:

```jsx
const total = useMemo(
  () => expenses.reduce((sum, e) => sum + e.amount, 0),
  [expenses]
);

const handleDelete = useCallback(
  (id) => dispatch({ type: "DELETE", payload: id }),
  [dispatch]
);
```

Only apply these when you've measured a bottleneck. Premature memoization adds complexity with no benefit.

## Code Splitting and Lazy Loading

Load JavaScript only when needed. React's `lazy` and `Suspense` make this straightforward:

```jsx
import { lazy, Suspense } from "react";

const AdminPanel = lazy(() => import("./AdminPanel"));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/admin" element={<AdminPanel />} />
      </Routes>
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

Use route-based splitting as the default strategy. For very heavy components (charts, editors), consider component-level lazy loading.

## Virtualization for Large Lists

Rendering thousands of DOM nodes kills performance. Virtualization libraries like `react-window` or `react-virtuoso` render only visible items:

```jsx
import { FixedSizeList } from "react-window";

<FixedSizeList height={600} itemCount={10000} itemSize={50}>
  {({ index, style }) => (
    <div style={style}>Row {index}</div>
  )}
</FixedSizeList>
```

This reduces DOM nodes from 10,000 to roughly 15–20, dramatically improving scroll performance and memory usage.

## State Management Best Practices

### Colocate State

Keep state as close to where it's used. Global state (Redux, Zustand) should hold only truly shared data.

### Avoid Prop Drilling

Drilling props through multiple layers causes unnecessary re-renders along the entire tree. Use composition or context selectively:

```jsx
function Page() {
  return (
    <Layout>
      <Sidebar>
        <SearchResults />
      </Sidebar>
    </Layout>
  );
}
```

### Context and Re-renders

React context consumers re-render on every context value change. Split large contexts into smaller, focused providers and memoize context values:

```jsx
const UserProvider = ({ children }) => {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  const value = useMemo(() => ({ user, setUser }), [user]);
  return <UserContext.Provider value={value}>{children}</UserContext.Provider>;
};
```

## Bundle Analysis

Use `vite-plugin-visualizer` or `webpack-bundle-analyzer` to audit bundle composition. Look for:

- Duplicate dependencies at different versions
- Large utility libraries (moment → date-fns is ~90% smaller)
- Tree-shakeable imports versus default imports

## Summary Checklist

- [ ] Measure with React DevTools Profiler before optimizing
- [ ] Apply React.memo on pure presentational components
- [ ] Use route-based code splitting by default
- [ ] Virtualize lists over ~100 items
- [ ] Memoize context values to prevent cascading re-renders
- [ ] Audit bundle size regularly
- [ ] Prefer composition over prop drilling
